  <subsection xml:id="subsubsec-rotational-symmetry-of-plane-figures" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Rotational Symmetry of Plane Figures</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the order of rotational symmetry of plane figures
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define rotational symmetry as the property of a shape that looks the same after being rotated less than <m>360°</m> about its centre. Define the order of rotational symmetry as the number of times a shape maps onto itself during a complete <m>360°</m> rotation. State the formula: Order <m>= 360° \div</m> smallest angle of rotation. Identify that all shapes have at least order 1 (<m>360°</m> rotation).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Determine the order of rotational symmetry for regular polygons and common shapes. Calculate the angle of rotation for each position. Identify shapes with no rotational symmetry (order 1) and shapes with rotational symmetry (order <m>\geq 2</m>). Apply the formula Order <m>= 360° \div</m> angle to solve problems.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Identify rotational symmetry in real-world objects and designs. Create patterns with specific orders of rotational symmetry. Analyse logos, signs, and decorative patterns for rotational symmetry.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
